Introduction

Introduced into the NBA in 1979, the 3-point shot added an entirely new dimension to the game of basketball. This simple arc around the basket now rewarded 3 points instead of the typical 2 points for a normal shot (field goal), but completely revolutionized how both players and coaches approached the game. However, even though this type of shot has now been in the game for decades, it has seemingly only recently seen explosive popularity. Once thought to maybe be “too risky” or “too inconsistent”, NBA players of the likes of Stephen Curry and James Harden (just to name a few) have now made this long-range shot a cornerstone of the current day NBA. The evolution of the 3-point shot in the NBA always fascinated me, so using an awesome data set on Kaggle and the principles of data science, I will explore how this shot has been utilized over time.

Getting Started

First, download the data set from the required tools above. Because the data is in the form of a CSV file, it will be very easy for us to use and manipulate. Although there are actually 3 CSV files in this dataset, we will only be using player_data.csv and Seasons_Stats.csv, as player_data.csv and Players.csv are very similar. Now, to get the data into R, we will use the aptly named function read_csv. Using the path to the CSV files in your computer, we can create variables holding the data.

# Replace the path to the csv with the correct patch for your specific computer
players <- read_csv("C:\\Users\\Eli Rudman\\Desktop\\CS\\320\\Final Project Data\\player_data.csv")
teams <- read_csv("C:\\Users\\Eli Rudman\\Desktop\\CS\\320\\Final Project Data\\Seasons_Stats.csv", col_types = cols(Player=col_character(), Pos=col_character(), Tm=col_character(), .default=col_double()))

However, some prior knowledge about the column types is needed here. The read_csv function is normally pretty good about detecting what datatype is appropriate for a column (Ex: A double for a quantity column, or character for a name column). However, because a lot of the data for players/teams is missing (especially for the earlier years of the data set), the read_csv function actually guesses the datatype incorrectly for a lot of the columns. Because of this, I specify what datatype I want the column to be parsed as when read_csv is parsing the data. Because most of the data is statistics, having double as the default datatype is a safe bet, but obviously it wouldn’t make sense for columns like the player’s name.

R uses a datatype called a data frame to hold these csv files. The two data frames we create can now be seen:

We can now get rid of some of the columns that are unnecessary for us. Similar to other programming languages, NULL can be used to achieve this by setting the entire column to NULL. We can also rename possibly cryptic column names.

# X1 is just an arbitrary index
teams$X1 <- NULL
teams$blank2 <- NULL
teams$blanl <- NULL
# Games started is not very important for us
teams$GS <- NULL

# Tm may be unclear, so rename to Team
teams <- teams %>% rename(Team=Tm)

Now, as mentioned above, the 3-point line actually wasn’t introduced into the NBA until the 1979-80 season, and from what I can tell, data wasn’t actually collected on it until the 1980-81 season. However, this data set includes data all the way back to 1950. Because of this, we can filter out the data prior to the 1980 season.

# If a player stopped playing before 1979, then they obviously never played with the 3-point line
players <- filter(players, year_end >= 1980)
# Seasons prior to 1979 also would not be relevant to us
teams <- filter(teams, Year >= 1980)

By performing these actions, our tables are now more appropriate for our research and easier to digest.

Exploring the Data

Now that our data is more suitable for what we want, we can perform analysis on it. This analysis will attempt to find overall trends and patterns in our data so that we can possibly begin to find relationships or correlations between variables.

To begin, we can start with some very simple but useful functions that R provides. For example, we can use arrange to sort the data on some criteria, in this case 3pt percentage. Also, because it is very easy to have a higher percentage with very low 3pt shots attempted, we require an arbitrary number of at least 200 3pt shots attempted in the season. Along with this, to make the data more managable, we select only the attributes that are pertinent to this specific query like the player’s name, the year, etc…

teams %>%
  filter(`3PA` > 200) %>%
  arrange(desc(`3P%`)) %>%
  # 3P% = the 3pt percentage and 3PA = their 3pt attempts
  select(Year, Player, Pos, Team, `3P%`, `3PA`)

Similar other functions include summarize and group_by. Summarize allows you to summarize an attribute value over all the entities in the data frame. For example, we can find the highest number of 3pt attempts in a season. Because na in R is essentially missing data, here we remove the missing data by setting na.rm to TRUE.

summarize(teams, `3pt attempts in a season`=max(`3PA`, na.rm=TRUE))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   `3pt attempts in a season`
##                        <dbl>
## 1                        886

Now with this data, we can also start to visualize the patterns with graphing. ggplot2 allows us to very easily do just that. For example, we can graph the same data we just found.

teams %>%
  group_by(Team, Year) %>%
  summarize(`3pt%`=mean(`3P%`, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(y=`3pt%`, x=Year)) +
  ggtitle("3pt Percentage by Team vs Year") +
  geom_point()

Already, we can begin to see a possible correlation between Year and the 3pt percentages of the teams. We can repeat this for some other possibly interesting relationships between variables.

Although I am a Golden State Warriors fan, so I am probably a bit biased in this regard, I would consider the Warriors to be one of the major teams that has led this 3pt shooting revolution. Because of this, lets look at specifically the Warriors, which will also probably be more digestible than the previous graph. Along with this, we can begin to look graphically at the possible relationships between the variables using a regression line (or the geom_smooth function).

teams %>%
  group_by(Team, Year) %>%
  filter(Team=='GSW') %>%
  summarize(`3pt%`=mean(`3P%`, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(y=`3pt%`, x=Year)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm) +
  ggtitle("Golden State Warriors 3pt % vs Year")

Along with this, we can look at how the number of 3pt shots attempted has changed over time.

teams %>%
  group_by(Team, Year) %>%
  filter(Team=='GSW') %>%
  summarize(`3pt shots attempted`=sum(`3PA`, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(y=`3pt shots attempted`, x=Year)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm) +
  ggtitle("Golden State Warriors 3pt Shots Attempted vs Year")

As we can now see, not only are the warriors getting better at 3pt shooting (have a higher 3pt percentage), but they are also taking significantly more 3pt shots than they used to. Indicating just how integral a part of the game 3pt shooting as become.

Looking at other notable 3pt shooting teams around the league, we can see how their 3pt shooting has varied over time as well. Along with this, we can use the help of color to differentiate the teams and make the graphs easier to read.

# Looking at the Warriors, the Rockets, the Clippers, the Trail Blazers, and the Nuggets
notable_teams <- c('GSW', 'HOU', 'LAC', 'POR', 'DEN')
teams %>%
  group_by(Team, Year) %>%
  filter(Team %in% notable_teams) %>%
  summarize(`3pt attempts`=sum(`3PA`, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_boxplot(mapping=aes(y=`3pt attempts`, x=Team)) +
  ggtitle("Notable 3pt Shooting Teams Range of 3pt Attempts")

teams %>%
  group_by(Team, Year) %>%
  filter(Team %in% notable_teams) %>%
  summarize(`3pt attempts`=sum(`3PA`, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(mapping=aes(y=`3pt attempts`, x=Year, color=Team)) +
  ggtitle("Notable 3pt Shooting Teams 3pt Attempts vs Time")

Data Transformations

It is usually very useful to think of data in the same uniform unit-less scale. Scaling the data solves this issue by transforming the data from “x” units in measurement, to “standard deviations away from the mean”. I scaled the 3pt attempts by year and compare them with the average 3pt attempts over all years. This can possible tell us that 3pt attempts used to be significantly lower because there are more years that are positive standard deviations away from the mean. This means that the years where 3pt attempts were low must have been very low, in order to lower the overall mean that much. However, this graph is still fairly difficult to read and can definitely still be improved.

teams %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarize(`3pt attempts`=mean(`3PA`, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(scaled_att = (`3pt attempts` - mean(`3pt attempts`)) / sd(`3pt attempts`)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=scaled_att)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=.25) +
  ggtitle("Scaled 3pt Attempts Grouped By Year")

This improvement can come from breaking the data into different quantiles, as we see that this leads to a much more even distribution.

teams %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarize(`3pt attempts`=mean(`3PA`, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(`3pt attempts disc`=cut(`3pt attempts`, breaks=quantile(`3pt attempts`, probs=seq(0,1,len=11), na.rm=TRUE))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=`3pt attempts disc`)) +
  geom_bar() +
  ggtitle("Scaled 3pt Attempts Grouped By Year Broken Into Quantiles")

Linear regression

As seen earlier, we used a combination of the geom_smooth function and the lm method to produce a line of best fit, or linear regression. We can again fit this with the league average 3pt percentages and attempts over time.

teams %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarize(`3pt attempts`=mean(`3PA`, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=`3pt attempts`)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm) +
  ggtitle("Linear Regression Fitted to Average 3pt Attempts by Year")

teams %>%
  group_by(Year) %>%
  summarize(`3pt percentage`=mean(`3P%`, na.rm=TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=`3pt percentage`)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm) +
  ggtitle("Linear Regression Fitted to Average 3pt Percentage by Year")

From this, we can see the weight of the year on the 3pt percentage and attempts. That is, the coefficient in the linear model that relates the two variables.

lm(`3P%`~Year, data=teams)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = `3P%` ~ Year, data = teams)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)         Year  
##   -7.068689     0.003658

We can interpret this result as the NBA as a whole getting ~.3 percent better at shooting 3-pointers every year. However, can we be sure this is accurate? To answer this question, we must construct a confidence interval. A confidence interval allows us to determine how precise our regression is. This can easily be achieved in R using the tidy() function included in the broom package, which includes very powerful functions for statistical analysis.

lm(`3P%`~Year, data=teams) %>%
  tidy()
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept) -7.07     0.259        -27.3 2.19e-160
## 2 Year         0.00366  0.000129      28.3 1.88e-171

Because the p-value is sufficiently small for the Year predictor in our regression, this allows us to produce our desired confidence interval. This confidence interval is constructed using the estimate +- the standard error, so we are able to say that on average the NBA gets .3 +- .00013 % better at shooting 3-pointers every year.

Conclusion

From the exploration conducted on our data, we can confidently say that the NBA is definitely shooting more 3-pointers and has also gotten significantly better at shooting 3-pointers as well. However, it will be interesting to see how this trend continues as NBA games are limited to 48 minutes, which I do not see changing anytime soon. It will be interesting to see if the 3 point attempts per game is reaching its peak, or will continue to increase for a while. This data set is also very extensive and could be used to answer many other interesting questions in the future. For example, it would be interesting to see the 3-point changes over time in the different positions of basketball, especially the centers or powerforwards. I would encourage the reader to download the dataset and conduct their own experiments.
